AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:37:04.879 --> 00:37:05.920
CARLA NAUMBURG: Oh, yeah.

00:37:05.920 --> 00:37:08.380
So the question was, does it
not work for kids under three?

00:37:08.380 --> 00:37:08.880
No.

00:37:08.880 --> 00:37:10.220
It definitely works
for kids under three.

00:37:10.220 --> 00:37:12.020
I mean, my publisher was
like, pick an age range.

00:37:12.020 --> 00:37:12.970
And I was like, OK.

00:37:12.970 --> 00:37:15.670
But I mean the reality is
it's all about figuring out

00:37:15.670 --> 00:37:16.790
what works for your kids.

00:37:16.790 --> 00:37:19.070
Like, under three
you can totally

00:37:19.070 --> 00:37:20.904
start doing these
activities with your kids.

00:37:20.904 --> 00:37:22.736
The ones that are going
to be most effective

00:37:22.736 --> 00:37:23.840
is the ones you practice.

00:37:23.840 --> 00:37:27.240
And then it sort of leaks out,
for lack of a better term,

00:37:27.240 --> 00:37:27.950
to your children.

00:37:27.950 --> 00:37:30.033
So when we can stay calm
when our children wake up

00:37:30.033 --> 00:37:33.940
from the nap screaming,
that's a great one.

00:37:33.940 --> 00:37:36.590
When we can let our
toddlers and little ones

00:37:36.590 --> 00:37:38.910
have the space and the time
to just play and explore

00:37:38.910 --> 00:37:42.330
the environment, and we're not
like getting in their space.

00:37:42.330 --> 00:37:43.830
And I never thought
this would be

00:37:43.830 --> 00:37:45.430
a thing I did until I had kids.

00:37:45.430 --> 00:37:47.100
But then, I'm like,
oh, you're playing.

00:37:47.100 --> 00:37:48.284
Let's make your play better.

00:37:48.284 --> 00:37:50.700
Like, let me get your space
and help you make that better.

00:37:50.700 --> 00:37:52.910
And Josh and I
stopped doing this

00:37:52.910 --> 00:37:55.780
when we read a quote by
Jack Black, the actor.

00:37:55.780 --> 00:37:59.689
He said in "USA Today," "never
give a happy child ice cream."

00:37:59.689 --> 00:38:00.480
And I was like, oh.

00:38:00.480 --> 00:38:01.430
That's right.

00:38:01.430 --> 00:38:04.290
I'll save the ice cream for
when maybe they're not so happy.

00:38:04.290 --> 00:38:05.570
Bribe them with ice cream.

00:38:05.570 --> 00:38:06.070
No.

00:38:06.070 --> 00:38:09.910
But like, if they're doing
well, leave them alone.

00:38:09.910 --> 00:38:12.640
And that's surprisingly hard
to do when it's especially me.

00:38:12.640 --> 00:38:13.950
I want to get like in it.

00:38:13.950 --> 00:38:15.390
And then Josh is
like, ice cream!

00:38:15.390 --> 00:38:17.130
And then I can like step away.

00:38:17.130 --> 00:38:20.100
So with the little
ones, and also food

00:38:20.100 --> 00:38:22.980
is a great time to let them
sort of mindfully be curious,

00:38:22.980 --> 00:38:24.050
if you can tolerate it.

00:38:24.050 --> 00:38:24.550
Right?

00:38:24.550 --> 00:38:26.280
Because then you end up with
food all over the place.

00:38:26.280 --> 00:38:27.730
And it's like, I
just gave you a bath

00:38:27.730 --> 00:38:29.271
and now you have
hummus in your hair.

00:38:29.271 --> 00:38:31.960
But if you can let them really
explore food and kind of sit

00:38:31.960 --> 00:38:33.376
with it and mush
it around, that's

00:38:33.376 --> 00:38:37.069
a great practice for
little ones, too.

00:38:37.069 --> 00:38:40.063
AUDIENCE: Do you have any tips
for parents in the moment?

00:38:40.063 --> 00:38:42.769
So when kids are freaking
out, the parents then

00:38:42.769 --> 00:38:44.060
are freaking out because of it.

00:38:44.060 --> 00:38:44.760
CARLA NAUMBURG: Yes.

00:38:44.760 --> 00:38:46.870
Tips for parents who are
freaking out in the moment.

00:38:46.870 --> 00:38:48.520
So that's what the
first book is about.

00:38:48.520 --> 00:38:50.550
It's called "Parenting
in the Present Moment."

00:38:50.550 --> 00:38:51.480
But briefly, yes.

00:38:51.480 --> 00:38:54.330
When you are freaking
out, my tips are,

00:38:54.330 --> 00:38:55.772
see if you can breathe.

00:38:55.772 --> 00:38:57.230
Like, pay attention
to your breath.

00:38:57.230 --> 00:38:59.510
And a lot of times people
think breathing meditation

00:38:59.510 --> 00:39:01.010
is this like whole big thing.

00:39:01.010 --> 00:39:03.676
Like, you have to breathe in for
four and breathe out for seven,

00:39:03.676 --> 00:39:06.250
and then stand on your head,
and then like chant a mantra.

00:39:06.250 --> 00:39:07.250
It's not.

00:39:07.250 --> 00:39:10.020
Just notice your breath,
however it is, wherever it is.

00:39:10.020 --> 00:39:11.521
Some people notice
it in their nose.

00:39:11.521 --> 00:39:13.061
Some people notice
it in their chest.

00:39:13.061 --> 00:39:14.660
Some people notice
it in their belly.

00:39:14.660 --> 00:39:15.980
Just notice.

00:39:15.980 --> 00:39:18.150
And that will like
calm you down.

00:39:18.150 --> 00:39:21.622
Another one is like, for some
people putting their hands

00:39:21.622 --> 00:39:22.330
on a counter top.

00:39:22.330 --> 00:39:24.550
That works for me kind
of to get grounded.

00:39:24.550 --> 00:39:26.180
For some people
just sitting down,

00:39:26.180 --> 00:39:29.460
like feeling your body in
contact with something firm

00:39:29.460 --> 00:39:31.624
can help you feel grounded.

00:39:31.624 --> 00:39:33.040
And then remembering
a few things.

00:39:33.040 --> 00:39:35.340
One is, unless your
child is in danger,

00:39:35.340 --> 00:39:37.430
you don't have to
react right away, which

00:39:37.430 --> 00:39:38.870
can be such a hard thing
when they're screaming.

00:39:38.870 --> 00:39:40.328
Like, they can
scream for a minute.

00:39:40.328 --> 00:39:43.860
They can tolerate it, especially
if they know that you're around

00:39:43.860 --> 00:39:44.759
and they're safe.

00:39:44.759 --> 00:39:46.300
And if they ask you
something and you

00:39:46.300 --> 00:39:47.550
don't know what to
do, like, you don't

00:39:47.550 --> 00:39:48.860
have to have an answer, right?

00:39:48.860 --> 00:39:52.400
You can say, I need some
time to think about that.

00:39:52.400 --> 00:39:56.020
And the other thing
is that you can always

00:39:56.020 --> 00:39:59.060
start a mindfulness practice
again and again and again.

00:39:59.060 --> 00:40:01.020
So there's a saying in
the mindfulness world,

00:40:01.020 --> 00:40:03.420
which is that it's really
easy to be mindful.

00:40:03.420 --> 00:40:06.280
It's really hard to
remember to be mindful.

00:40:06.280 --> 00:40:09.114
And so some of us will get to
this place where it's like, ah.

00:40:09.114 --> 00:40:11.280
It's the end of the day,
and I forgot to do laundry,

00:40:11.280 --> 00:40:12.190
and I forgot to be mindful.

00:40:12.190 --> 00:40:13.360
I totally screwed that up.

00:40:13.360 --> 00:40:14.720
And then we beat
ourselves up, because we

00:40:14.720 --> 00:40:15.969
want to be these calm parents.

00:40:15.969 --> 00:40:17.510
And instead we
yelled at our kids.

00:40:17.510 --> 00:40:20.786
So that moment when you
notice that you're ramped up,

00:40:20.786 --> 00:40:22.160
that you're a
million miles away,

00:40:22.160 --> 00:40:24.080
that you're yelling
whatever it is,

00:40:24.080 --> 00:40:25.590
that's what Sharon
Salzberg-- who

00:40:25.590 --> 00:40:29.830
is a very well-regarded and
one of the leading meditation

00:40:29.830 --> 00:40:32.600
teachers in this country--
she calls it the Magic Moment.

00:40:32.600 --> 00:40:35.650
Any moment you notice
and become aware,

00:40:35.650 --> 00:40:37.470
I am losing it with
my kid, is the moment

00:40:37.470 --> 00:40:39.220
you can choose to make
a different choice.

00:40:39.220 --> 00:40:41.261
And every once in a while
I have enough awareness

00:40:41.261 --> 00:40:44.050
that I will actually stop
yelling at my kids mid-yell.

00:40:44.050 --> 00:40:46.520
And it's surprisingly
effective, because they're

00:40:46.520 --> 00:40:47.440
expecting this rant.

00:40:47.440 --> 00:40:48.800
And then all of a
sudden, you just stop.

00:40:48.800 --> 00:40:49.780
And they're like, whoa.

00:40:49.780 --> 00:40:50.810
What happened?

00:40:50.810 --> 00:40:54.260
And so whenever you can catch
it, you can always stop.

00:40:54.260 --> 00:40:56.740
And we also have this
thing with parenting

00:40:56.740 --> 00:40:58.486
that we have to be
consistent, right?

00:40:58.486 --> 00:41:00.110
So once you've laid
the law down, like,

00:41:00.110 --> 00:41:01.970
you cannot change
your mind ever.

00:41:01.970 --> 00:41:03.800
It's actually not true.

00:41:03.800 --> 00:41:04.660
We make mistakes.

00:41:04.660 --> 00:41:05.710
We say the wrong thing.

00:41:05.710 --> 00:41:07.040
We set a limit that's
not the right one.

00:41:07.040 --> 00:41:08.456
Or we don't set
enough of a limit.

00:41:08.456 --> 00:41:10.860
You can go back and say,
actually, I changed my mind.

00:41:10.860 --> 00:41:11.610
Right?

00:41:11.610 --> 00:41:14.450
But it's important
that we when it can,

00:41:14.450 --> 00:41:16.684
it comes from a mindful
place, as opposed to,

00:41:16.684 --> 00:41:17.850
I'm going to set this limit.

00:41:17.850 --> 00:41:18.960
But now you're being
a jerk about it.

00:41:18.960 --> 00:41:19.850
And I don't really
want to fight with you.

00:41:19.850 --> 00:41:20.330
I'm tired.

00:41:20.330 --> 00:41:21.960
I just want you to go to bed
so I can watch my TV show,

00:41:21.960 --> 00:41:23.251
so I'm going to change my mind.

00:41:23.251 --> 00:41:24.970
Like, that's not
really so effective.

00:41:24.970 --> 00:41:26.390
But when you can say, huh.

00:41:26.390 --> 00:41:29.120
Now that I'm calm, I realize
I didn't actually mean that.

00:41:29.120 --> 00:41:30.020
That's a better way.

00:41:30.020 --> 00:41:31.640
But check out the first book.
"Parenting in the Present

00:41:31.640 --> 00:41:31.870
Moment."

00:41:31.870 --> 00:41:32.870
It's got some good tips.

00:41:32.870 --> 00:41:33.730
And also, last tip.

00:41:33.730 --> 00:41:35.396
And then I see there's
another question.

00:41:35.396 --> 00:41:37.819
Start practicing this
when you're calm.

00:41:37.819 --> 00:41:39.860
Because just like we talked
about with your kids,

00:41:39.860 --> 00:41:42.150
you can't teach them a new
skill when they're freaking out.

00:41:42.150 --> 00:41:44.390
We can't teach ourselves a new
skill when we're freaking out.

00:41:44.390 --> 00:41:46.450
So if we expect ourselves
to be able to start

00:41:46.450 --> 00:41:48.810
a mindfulness practice
when our kids are

00:41:48.810 --> 00:41:51.560
like really pushing our buttons,
it's not going to happen.

00:41:51.560 --> 00:41:53.900
So either try meditation,
which is a great one.

00:41:53.900 --> 00:41:55.900
Or if you're like, I am
not sitting on a cushion

00:41:55.900 --> 00:41:57.594
right now, that's
not happening, lady,

00:41:57.594 --> 00:41:59.010
then the other
thing you can do is

00:41:59.010 --> 00:42:01.800
pick one or two activities
you know you do every day,

00:42:01.800 --> 00:42:03.326
and pay attention to them.

00:42:03.326 --> 00:42:04.700
And when your mind
wanders, as it

00:42:04.700 --> 00:42:06.630
will after about two
seconds, come back.

00:42:06.630 --> 00:42:08.154
So for me it's taking a shower.

00:42:08.154 --> 00:42:09.570
I can get to the
end of my shower.

00:42:09.570 --> 00:42:10.380
My hair is wet.

00:42:10.380 --> 00:42:11.700
I have no idea if I washed it.

00:42:11.700 --> 00:42:12.620
Not a clue.

00:42:12.620 --> 00:42:15.830
And so can you pick one or
two things you enjoy doing.

00:42:15.830 --> 00:42:17.660
Don't make it harder
than it has to be.

00:42:17.660 --> 00:42:18.956
Drinking your coffee.

00:42:18.956 --> 00:42:19.830
Reading to your kids.

00:42:19.830 --> 00:42:20.500
Whatever it is.

00:42:20.500 --> 00:42:21.840
And just pay attention.

00:42:21.840 --> 00:42:23.650
So those are things
that will help.

00:42:23.650 --> 00:42:26.050
And the more you do that, the
more your brain gets better

00:42:26.050 --> 00:42:28.540
at noticing, the more likely
you will be to notice.

00:42:28.540 --> 00:42:29.040
Yeah.

00:42:29.040 --> 00:42:31.140
Please.

00:42:31.140 --> 00:42:32.892
AUDIENCE: This book looks great.

00:42:32.892 --> 00:42:34.600
I'm really looking
forward to reading it.

00:42:34.600 --> 00:42:34.950
CARLA NAUMBURG: Thanks.

00:42:34.950 --> 00:42:36.930
AUDIENCE: One
place that where we

00:42:36.930 --> 00:42:39.030
found the good ideas
tend to break down

00:42:39.030 --> 00:42:41.370
is when you have multiple kids.

00:42:41.370 --> 00:42:45.860
And I'm curious to know whether
the book addresses it or not.

00:42:45.860 --> 00:42:48.220
I'm thinking of the
calm down space.

00:42:48.220 --> 00:42:52.505
In my house that would turn
into the thunderdome, basically.

00:42:52.505 --> 00:42:54.340
One kid we could maybe do that.

00:42:54.340 --> 00:42:57.600
But then, especially if there's
just one parent at home,

00:42:57.600 --> 00:43:00.540
you got to go make dinner.

00:43:00.540 --> 00:43:02.770
And usually we try good ideas.

00:43:02.770 --> 00:43:04.527
And then it's either
yelling or TV.

00:43:04.527 --> 00:43:06.610
You know, it's like, those
become our two options.

00:43:06.610 --> 00:43:08.040
So I'm just curious.

00:43:08.040 --> 00:43:10.750
When you're outnumbered,
anything in the book

00:43:10.750 --> 00:43:11.667
or otherwise that--

00:43:11.667 --> 00:43:13.416
CARLA NAUMBURG: How
many kids do you have?

00:43:13.416 --> 00:43:14.677
AUDIENCE: Three so far.

00:43:14.677 --> 00:43:15.510
CARLA NAUMBURG: Yes.

00:43:15.510 --> 00:43:16.890
So you are well outnumbered.

00:43:16.890 --> 00:43:17.880
You know, this is
a huge problem.

00:43:17.880 --> 00:43:19.421
So the calm down
space, you're right.

00:43:19.421 --> 00:43:22.100
This is a big issue
that comes up.

00:43:22.100 --> 00:43:24.360
But you can still do it
with the calm down space,

00:43:24.360 --> 00:43:25.400
even with multiple kids.

00:43:25.400 --> 00:43:27.485
And like in my daughters'
classrooms-- in every classroom

00:43:27.485 --> 00:43:29.284
at my daughter's school
from K through 8,

00:43:29.284 --> 00:43:30.450
they have a calm down space.

00:43:30.450 --> 00:43:32.000
That's one space
for like 24 kids.

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:32.970
So they have to take turns.

00:43:32.970 --> 00:43:34.550
And my daughter will come
home frustrated sometimes

00:43:34.550 --> 00:43:35.758
that she didn't get her turn.

00:43:35.758 --> 00:43:36.510
That's fine.

00:43:36.510 --> 00:43:39.180
So having a space in the
house is a good idea.

00:43:39.180 --> 00:43:39.860
But yes.

00:43:39.860 --> 00:43:43.250
When all three kids
are melting down,

00:43:43.250 --> 00:43:45.969
that's when you have to put down
the knife-- which I'm making

00:43:45.969 --> 00:43:47.260
reference to my own experience.

00:43:47.260 --> 00:43:48.968
I'm not implying you
carry knives around.

00:43:48.968 --> 00:43:50.580
Although--

00:43:50.580 --> 00:43:51.810
And go be with them.

00:43:51.810 --> 00:43:53.260
And that's a moment.

00:43:53.260 --> 00:43:56.640
So one of the words that comes
up a lot in mindfulness world

00:43:56.640 --> 00:43:57.251
is acceptance.

00:43:57.251 --> 00:43:58.750
I don't love that
word, because it's

00:43:58.750 --> 00:44:01.291
like we have to accept and just
be OK that our kids are going

00:44:01.291 --> 00:44:02.220
to like, cry forever.

00:44:02.220 --> 00:44:04.130
I like the word
acknowledgement better.

00:44:04.130 --> 00:44:06.030
You have to just
acknowledge in that moment

00:44:06.030 --> 00:44:07.305
that everyone is melting down.

00:44:07.305 --> 00:44:09.180
And you have to make
the best choice you can.

00:44:09.180 --> 00:44:11.510
And sometimes the
best choice is TV.

00:44:11.510 --> 00:44:13.350
Like, practicing
mindfulness does not

00:44:13.350 --> 00:44:17.370
mean we do the number one
best parenting intervention

00:44:17.370 --> 00:44:17.929
at all times.

00:44:17.929 --> 00:44:19.470
And in fact, I would
argue that's not

00:44:19.470 --> 00:44:21.902
helpful for your kids,
because then your kids learn

00:44:21.902 --> 00:44:23.360
that all of their
needs will be met

00:44:23.360 --> 00:44:25.401
in the most effective way
at every moment-- which

00:44:25.401 --> 00:44:27.350
guess what-- is not
how the world works.

00:44:27.350 --> 00:44:28.740
So sometimes you yell.

00:44:28.740 --> 00:44:30.430
Sometimes you turn on the TV.

00:44:30.430 --> 00:44:31.856
But when your kids
are old enough

00:44:31.856 --> 00:44:33.230
that you can start
to strategize,

00:44:33.230 --> 00:44:35.729
like can one of them go to their
rooms if they need a break,

00:44:35.729 --> 00:44:36.380
by choice.

00:44:36.380 --> 00:44:38.700
Can you use the
calm down corner?

00:44:38.700 --> 00:44:40.610
Maybe a kid needs to
plug-in some headphones

00:44:40.610 --> 00:44:42.026
and listen to a
guided meditation.

00:44:44.405 --> 00:44:46.972
I mean, it really involves
a lot of creativity.

00:44:46.972 --> 00:44:48.680
But you can do it with
more than one kid.

00:44:48.680 --> 00:44:50.970
You just can't expect to do
it perfectly all the time.

00:44:50.970 --> 00:44:54.060
And that's when the
self-compassion and kindness

00:44:54.060 --> 00:44:55.490
and curiosity is
really important,

00:44:55.490 --> 00:44:57.060
because it's like, oh.

00:44:57.060 --> 00:44:58.350
I just lost it.

00:44:58.350 --> 00:45:01.010
And so can I be nice to
myself and forgive myself.

00:45:01.010 --> 00:45:04.670
Because most of us when we
do an unskilful parenting

00:45:04.670 --> 00:45:07.264
intervention, we tend to
beat ourselves up about it.

00:45:07.264 --> 00:45:08.180
I'm a terrible parent.

00:45:08.180 --> 00:45:09.263
I can't believe I lost it.

00:45:09.263 --> 00:45:11.710
Everybody else is
doing it better.

00:45:11.710 --> 00:45:12.782
And then we get stuck.

00:45:12.782 --> 00:45:14.240
And then our kids
come in the room.

00:45:14.240 --> 00:45:15.948
And we bite their
heads off because we're

00:45:15.948 --> 00:45:16.960
in a bad head space.

00:45:16.960 --> 00:45:18.200
So when you can be like, OK.

00:45:18.200 --> 00:45:19.060
Well, that was a rough moment.

00:45:19.060 --> 00:45:20.030
Glad that's over.

00:45:20.030 --> 00:45:23.250
And thank God for TV, because
it's really useful sometimes.

00:45:23.250 --> 00:45:26.270
Then you're much more likely
to have a batterer intervention

00:45:26.270 --> 00:45:26.770
next time.

00:45:26.770 --> 00:45:27.960
But it's tricky.

00:45:27.960 --> 00:45:29.682
Multiple kids is tricky.

00:45:29.682 --> 00:45:31.640
You can also do little
group meditation things.

00:45:31.640 --> 00:45:35.737
Like I'll get my girls together
and we do practices together.

00:45:35.737 --> 00:45:37.445
And again, this comes
back to starting it

00:45:37.445 --> 00:45:38.810
when everybody's
in a good space,

00:45:38.810 --> 00:45:40.240
because the more you
try to just start it

00:45:40.240 --> 00:45:41.540
when they're in a bad space,
you're setting everyone

00:45:41.540 --> 00:45:43.000
up for failure.

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:45.870
And then maybe boarding school.

00:45:45.870 --> 00:45:46.600
I don't know.

00:45:46.600 --> 00:45:47.820
That could help.

00:45:47.820 --> 00:45:49.570
Was somebody over here
who had a question?

00:45:49.570 --> 00:45:52.349
AUDIENCE: I have a question
about siblings arguing.

00:45:52.349 --> 00:45:54.140
CARLA NAUMBURG: It was
the sibling arguing.

00:45:54.140 --> 00:45:54.430
OK.

00:45:54.430 --> 00:45:56.179
So here's the thing
about sibling arguing.

00:45:56.179 --> 00:45:57.810
I am not an expert
in sibling arguing.

00:45:57.810 --> 00:45:59.435
And I did a lot of
it when I was a kid.

00:45:59.435 --> 00:46:02.330
And my girls do it now.

00:46:02.330 --> 00:46:05.720
Laura Markham has a
book-- M-A-R-K-H-A-M--

00:46:05.720 --> 00:46:10.130
about sibling rivalry that
I've heard good stuff about.

00:46:10.130 --> 00:46:13.160
But I think that remembering
that it's normal,

00:46:13.160 --> 00:46:14.667
like some amount
of it is normal.

00:46:14.667 --> 00:46:16.750
I mean, I saw some statistic
that kids get into it

00:46:16.750 --> 00:46:18.458
with their siblings
like once every seven

00:46:18.458 --> 00:46:20.680
seconds or something.

00:46:20.680 --> 00:46:21.629
Yikes.

00:46:21.629 --> 00:46:23.920
But that it's an important
part of their socialization.

00:46:23.920 --> 00:46:26.010
Like, that's how they
learn to figure things out.

00:46:26.010 --> 00:46:28.440
And what I would say--
and this isn't necessarily

00:46:28.440 --> 00:46:30.887
a mindfulness bit-- is
depending on how old they are

00:46:30.887 --> 00:46:33.220
and if everybody's safe, can
you just get out of the way

00:46:33.220 --> 00:46:34.510
and encourage them
to figure it out.

00:46:34.510 --> 00:46:36.720
And one of my friends, what
she'll do is she'll say,

00:46:36.720 --> 00:46:38.928
either you guys figure it
out, or I take away the toy

00:46:38.928 --> 00:46:40.090
and you go to your room.

00:46:40.090 --> 00:46:41.810
And you give them a choice.

00:46:41.810 --> 00:46:44.360
But again, different families
have so much different stuff

00:46:44.360 --> 00:46:46.524
going on that the sibling
stuff is really tricky.

00:46:46.524 --> 00:46:48.440
I find the other really
good trick for sibling

00:46:48.440 --> 00:46:51.747
is make sure everybody is
fed and well-slept, which

00:46:51.747 --> 00:46:52.830
is like a good life thing.

00:46:52.830 --> 00:46:55.246
Our worst sibling fights are
in the afternoon when they're

00:46:55.246 --> 00:46:56.490
tired and they're worn out.

00:46:56.490 --> 00:46:58.692
And then I just have to
like work really hard

00:46:58.692 --> 00:47:00.150
to get them set up
in some activity

00:47:00.150 --> 00:47:02.100
that involves relatively
little interaction,

00:47:02.100 --> 00:47:04.350
because they can't handle it.

00:47:04.350 --> 00:47:05.510
Other questions?

00:47:05.510 --> 00:47:06.211
Thoughts?

00:47:06.211 --> 00:47:06.710
Yeah.

00:47:06.710 --> 00:47:07.230
Jessie.

00:47:07.230 --> 00:47:09.922
AUDIENCE: So thinking
about being mindful

00:47:09.922 --> 00:47:11.380
and how I would do
that in my life.

00:47:11.380 --> 00:47:15.770
I worry that time pressure
is the enemy of mindfulness,

00:47:15.770 --> 00:47:19.270
and that a lot of times
the intense moments all

00:47:19.270 --> 00:47:20.830
have a time pressure aspect.

00:47:20.830 --> 00:47:23.080
Like, I need to get
this done by this time,

00:47:23.080 --> 00:47:24.960
or get over to this place.

00:47:24.960 --> 00:47:28.257
And taking a step back and
slowing down feels very hard.

00:47:28.257 --> 00:47:29.090
CARLA NAUMBURG: Yes.

00:47:29.090 --> 00:47:29.589
I agree.

00:47:29.589 --> 00:47:31.340
And I think we can
all relate to you.

00:47:31.340 --> 00:47:34.560
And certainly you can
move fast and be mindful.

00:47:34.560 --> 00:47:35.440
There's no question.

00:47:35.440 --> 00:47:37.500
Mindfulness does not
require us to be slow,

00:47:37.500 --> 00:47:38.880
but it's just easier.

00:47:38.880 --> 00:47:39.770
Right?

00:47:39.770 --> 00:47:43.902
And so what I would argue
is that there are always

00:47:43.902 --> 00:47:46.360
going to be days and moments
when you just feel like you're

00:47:46.360 --> 00:47:48.550
moving at 100 miles an hour.

00:47:48.550 --> 00:47:50.280
I think the trick is
to convince yourself

00:47:50.280 --> 00:47:52.696
that you don't actually have
to move at 100 miles an hour.

00:47:52.696 --> 00:47:54.720
And you'll be more
effective if you don't.

00:47:54.720 --> 00:47:56.770
And my best example
is I'll get really

00:47:56.770 --> 00:47:58.190
stressed when I'm trying to get
out the door in the morning.

00:47:58.190 --> 00:47:59.550
And I'm trying to make
the lunches or whatever.

00:47:59.550 --> 00:48:02.110
Although, in all fairness, Josh
make lunches most mornings.

00:48:02.110 --> 00:48:03.109
I have to give him that.

00:48:03.109 --> 00:48:05.030
But when I'm trying to
get everything together

00:48:05.030 --> 00:48:07.238
and what inevitably happens
is I drop the blueberries

00:48:07.238 --> 00:48:08.140
all over the floor.

00:48:08.140 --> 00:48:09.682
Or I've have got
everyone in the car.

00:48:09.682 --> 00:48:11.515
And I realize that I've
forgotten something.

00:48:11.515 --> 00:48:12.500
And we have to go back.

00:48:12.500 --> 00:48:14.910
And so when we can start to
convince ourselves that when

00:48:14.910 --> 00:48:18.529
we can practice a little
bit of mindfulness,

00:48:18.529 --> 00:48:20.820
it'll actually make things
go faster and more smoothly.

00:48:20.820 --> 00:48:22.778
And when I say a little
bit, I mean, literally.

00:48:22.778 --> 00:48:25.180
Can you stop and stand and
take three deep breaths.

00:48:25.180 --> 00:48:28.279
And then ask yourself,
what do I need to do now?

00:48:28.279 --> 00:48:30.320
Or if you're staring down
the barrel of an insane

00:48:30.320 --> 00:48:32.050
day with a ton of meetings
and all these projects,

00:48:32.050 --> 00:48:33.716
can you stop and take
some deep breaths.

00:48:33.716 --> 00:48:36.520
And if you're a person who
likes to write things down,

00:48:36.520 --> 00:48:39.170
can you sort of make yourself
a quick list and say,

00:48:39.170 --> 00:48:40.810
what are the things
I need to focus on?

00:48:40.810 --> 00:48:42.750
Because when our
brains get going,

00:48:42.750 --> 00:48:44.546
it's that forward
thinking, we get so

00:48:44.546 --> 00:48:45.920
wrapped up in
everything that has

00:48:45.920 --> 00:48:48.211
to happen in the future, and
all the worries about what

00:48:48.211 --> 00:48:50.800
if I don't get this done,
that we end up just reacting.

00:48:50.800 --> 00:48:52.680
Like, oh, now this thing
popped in my brain,

00:48:52.680 --> 00:48:53.680
so I'm going to do this.

00:48:53.680 --> 00:48:54.850
And then this thing
popped in my brain.

00:48:54.850 --> 00:48:55.810
So I'm going to do this.

00:48:55.810 --> 00:48:57.390
And that may not be
the most skillful way

00:48:57.390 --> 00:48:58.250
to approach the day.

00:48:58.250 --> 00:49:00.780
It may be better to take
a few-- it could literally

00:49:00.780 --> 00:49:03.550
be five minutes, which I would
argue that since most of us

00:49:03.550 --> 00:49:05.299
aren't the President
of the United States,

00:49:05.299 --> 00:49:06.570
we actually have five minutes.

00:49:06.570 --> 00:49:08.370
We can sit down
and say, what are

00:49:08.370 --> 00:49:09.620
the things I need to do today?

00:49:09.620 --> 00:49:13.250
What are the most effective
ways to plan my day?

00:49:13.250 --> 00:49:16.790
And then when stuff pops up, we
have this map in our mind of,

00:49:16.790 --> 00:49:17.290
OK.

00:49:17.290 --> 00:49:18.740
But this is what I
was going to do today.

00:49:18.740 --> 00:49:20.323
And is that thing
that just popped up,

00:49:20.323 --> 00:49:23.036
is that worthy of intruding
on this space and time?

00:49:23.036 --> 00:49:24.660
And it's the same
thing with parenting.

00:49:24.660 --> 00:49:26.980
If I can go into the
afternoon with a plan,

00:49:26.980 --> 00:49:28.430
I'm gonna give my girls a snack.

00:49:28.430 --> 00:49:29.580
And then we're going
to have some play time.

00:49:29.580 --> 00:49:30.920
And then I'm gonna make dinner.

00:49:30.920 --> 00:49:34.130
And then something pops up, I
can sort of make this choice.

00:49:34.130 --> 00:49:36.980
Is this the most skillful place
to put my attention right now?

00:49:36.980 --> 00:49:37.836
And sometimes it is.

00:49:37.836 --> 00:49:40.210
Sometimes we just have to
react, especially in parenting.

00:49:40.210 --> 00:49:41.680
Like, when your kid's about
to fall down the stairs,

00:49:41.680 --> 00:49:43.810
you've got to drop whatever
you're doing, go grab them.

00:49:43.810 --> 00:49:45.393
But more often than
not, I would argue

00:49:45.393 --> 00:49:46.890
we react when we don't need to.

00:49:46.890 --> 00:49:52.130
So I think small amounts
of time on a busy day

00:49:52.130 --> 00:49:55.350
can make you actually be more
effective during the day.

00:49:55.350 --> 00:49:57.410
This book is on Amazon
and local bookstores.

00:49:57.410 --> 00:49:58.740
And then "Parenting
in the Present Moment"

00:49:58.740 --> 00:50:00.000
is my first book,
which is really

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:02.370
meant more for parents who
want to practice mindfulness.

00:50:02.370 --> 00:50:03.850
And I just really
appreciate you all coming.

00:50:03.850 --> 00:50:04.350
Thank you.

00:50:04.350 --> 00:50:08.300
[APPLAUSE]

